Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add the @chicken stock powder{1}, stir in the @basmati rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a lid on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} or #wok{} on medium-high heat. When hot, add the @diced chicken thigh{260%g} and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Fry, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. As the chicken sizzles away, halve the @plum{2}, remove the stones and chop each half into 1 cm chunks. Add the plum pieces to the pan with the chicken and continue cooking for ~{1%minute}.

While everything is cooking, trim the @pak choi{1} then thinly slice widthways. Trim the @spring onion{1} and thinly slice. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @red chilli{1/2}, deseed and finely chop. Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}. Chop half the lime into wedges.

Add the pak choi, garlic and chilli to the pan. Cook, stirring regularly until the pak choi has softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @hoisin sauce{64%ml}, @ketjap manis{25%ml} and @sugar{1/2%tsp}. Add 1 tbsp water per person and squeeze in half the lime juice, ensuring everything is well coated.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Fluff the rice up with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest. Share the rice between your #bowls{} and top with the stir-fry. Finish with a sprinkle of spring onion and add a lime wedge for squeezing over. Enjoy!